<font color="#FF0000">PTSD AND THE FAMILY</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 12  1:11:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
My husband served in Phan Rang, Vietnam in 1966.  When he came home he never talked about what he had experienced.  Then in 1987 he suffered a heart attack resulting in open heart surgery.  He was admitted to our local VAMC for chest pains in 1989 and the outcome of tests showed he suffered from anxiety.  He began seeing a therapist at the hospital and after many tests he was diagnosed with PTSD.  We had never heard of this disorder and had to do research ourselves to find answers. My children and I had blamed ourselves for the outbursts of anger and his always wanting to be alone.  I was always making excuses for their father and was their emotional protection.  My husband never was physically violent, but the uncontrolled outbursts were disheartening.  When he was finally receiving treatment for the disorder and we learned more about PTSD it made our lives much better.  Vietnam has been in our lives for 31 years and I believe it will continue to be here forever, but the best part is we understand more about the effects.  My heart goes out to the vets and their families who suffer the effects of PTSD but don't yet know what the problem is. For any family member out there who has a loved one with problems there is help available at the VAMCs.  Not just for the vet, but for the families too. 
<p><code>-- jdm@sat.net  (Deborah Copeland) </code><p>


